1) API surface and signatures
parseCron(expression: string) -> ParsedCron
- Inputs: expression (string). Accepts 5-field standard crons (minute hour day month weekday) and optional 6-field with seconds. Accepts special shortcut strings @yearly, @monthly, @weekly, @daily, @hourly.
- Returns: ParsedCron object with explicit fields: seconds?(0-59), minutes(0-59 set or range/list/step), hours(0-23), dayOfMonth(1-31), month(1-12), dayOfWeek(0-7 where both 0 and 7 represent Sunday), plus metadata: originalExpression, hasSeconds(boolean), specialShortcut|null.
- Behavior: throws SyntaxError with descriptive message on invalid tokens or out-of-range values.

nextRun(expression: string, after?: Date|string) -> Date
- Inputs: expression (string) or ParsedCron accepted; after optional Date or ISO string (defaults to now in UTC-aware local time).
- Returns: the next Date strictly after `after` that matches the expression.
- Behavior: deterministically computes next occurrence; never returns same instant as `after` unless expression explicitly matches a time strictly later.

nextRuns(expression: string, count: number, after?: Date|string) -> Date[]
- Inputs: count (positive integer).
- Returns: array of `count` Date objects in chronological order; throws RangeError if count < 1 or exceeds internal safety limit (configurable; default 10_000).

matches(expression: string, date: Date|string) -> boolean
- Returns true if given date matches the parsed cron expression (accounting for seconds field if present).

toString(parsed: ParsedCron) -> string
- Converts parsed object back to a normalized cron string in canonical field order (include seconds if hasSeconds true).

2) Cron syntax supported
- Fields: seconds (optional), minutes, hours, day-of-month, month, day-of-week.
- Operators: wildcard (*), ranges (A-B), lists (A,B,C), steps (*/N or A-B/N), single values.
- Aliases: month names (Jan-Dec) and weekday names (Sun-Sat) supported; case-insensitive.
- Special strings mapping: @yearly -> 0 0 1 1 *, @monthly -> 0 0 1 * *, @weekly -> 0 0 * * 0, @daily -> 0 0 * * *, @hourly -> 0 * * * *.

3) Parsing rules and data model
- Tokenization: split on whitespace for fields, accept either 5 or 6 fields (6 => seconds present). Accept leading/trailing spaces. Recognize exact special strings before tokenization.
- Normalization: expand lists and ranges into canonical internal representations but keep original spec for toString. Represent each field as one of: wildcard(true), set of discrete integers, or step descriptor {start,end,step}.
- Validation ranges: seconds 0-59, minutes 0-59, hours 0-23, day-of-month 1-31, month 1-12, day-of-week 0-7 (0 and 7 -> Sunday).
- Error messages: include field name, offending token, and allowed range (e.g., "Invalid day-of-month token '32' — allowed 1..31").

4) Next-run computation algorithm (deterministic, iterative roll-forward)
- Input: ParsedCron and start "after" timestamp.
- Use component-wise roll-forward algorithm starting from seconds (if present) up to years: set candidate = after + 1 second/millisecond to ensure strict "next" behavior.
- For each field (seconds, minutes, hours, day, month, year):
  - If candidate value matches field constraint, proceed to next field.
  - If not, advance the current field to the next allowed value and zero-out all less-significant fields to their minimum allowed values, then re-check subsequent fields.
- Day-of-month and day-of-week interaction: standard behavior is OR (match if either field matches) unless explicit configuration requires AND. Default: OR, but allow option to require both via parse option requireBothDayFields=false.
- Month length handling: when advancing day-of-month beyond month length, increment month and set day to the lowest matching day in that month.
- Leap-year handling: compute month lengths using Gregorian rules; treat Feb 29 as valid only in leap years.
- DST: compute using target timezone semantics (default system local). Recommended: perform calculations in UTC whenever possible and map final Date to intended timezone. For local-time semantics, detect DST forward jumps (missing local times) and treat a missing match as the next available valid local time, not an error. For repeated local times at DST fallbacks, return both instances in chronological order when iterating multiple runs.
- Performance: stop search and throw if year exceeds after.getFullYear() + 100 by default (configurable maxYears) to avoid infinite loops.

5) Edge cases and DST/leap-year handling
- Missing dates (e.g., 30 Feb): advance to next valid occurrence in subsequent months; do not throw unless expression explicitly references impossible absolute date ranges for all future years.
- Day-of-week vs day-of-month conflicts: default OR semantics; document and allow configuration to switch to AND.
- Timezones: APIs accept an optional timezone parameter (IANA tz string). If provided, computations must use that timezone for matching and DST rules; otherwise use UTC for calculation then convert to local Date object if requested.

6) Validation and error semantics
- parseCron throws SyntaxError for malformed tokens, RangeError for out-of-range numeric values, TypeError when input types are invalid.
- matches and nextRun accept either string or ParsedCron; when given string, they invoke parseCron and propagate parse errors.
- nextRuns validates positive integer count; throws RangeError when count <= 0 or exceeds configurable safety limit.

7) Testing and acceptance criteria (from MISSION.md)
- Unit test suites must include:
  - Basic parsing: wildcards, ranges, lists, steps, named months/days.
  - API signatures and return types.
  - nextRun and nextRuns correctness for typical schedules (daily, weekly, monthly) and edge cases (month-end, DST transitions, leap years).
  - matches correctness for boundary values including seconds when present.
  - Invalid inputs produce descriptive exceptions.
- Acceptance checklist:
  - parseCron("*/15 * * * *") returns a parsed object.
  - nextRun("0 9 * * 1") returns next Monday 09:00.
  - matches("0 0 25 12 *", new Date("2025-12-25")) -> true.
  - nextRuns("@daily", 7) -> seven consecutive daily dates.
  - DST transitions handled: no duplicated or skipped runs when counting in local time semantics.

